Market Access Exporters of agri-food products to Malaysia face a number of challenges when entering the market.
The market for imported foods continues to be liberalized as tariffs are reduced for most products.
Luxury goods are heavily taxed, while goods such as raw materials, essential foodstuffs, and pharmaceutical products are subject to reduced duties.
Many other goods, which are to be used in Malaysia’s development, also benefit from lower duties.
Although tariffs have been reduced on a number of goods, certain sectors still have high rates in order to regulate imports.
Certification Requirements Imported meat products must be from approved halal facilities because the products cannot be sold to Muslims in Malaysia unless they are certified halal.
Imports from China also require special permits.
If a specific license is not required, a "Declaration of Goods Imported" form must be filled out at the point of import.
Documentation is generally handled by international freight forwarders.
Packaging and Labelling All imported consumer goods must be affixed with a label identifying the importing agent.
This is generally done after the goods have cleared customs.
Processed food products must show the name of the manufacturer and packer or importer on the product label as well as the weight or volume, common name, brand, content or list of ingredients in accordance to proportion by weight, animal product content, alcohol content, additives and storage instructions.
Expiry dates are required on certain produce, perishable foods, and goods with short shelf lives.
Nutritional information is optional except for baby food, processed food for children, cereal and food for dietary purposes.
