BAS The Philippines is still a net importer of rice despite the mandate of AFMA for self-sufficiency.
There were minimal imports in 1993-1995 but a sharp surge was experienced in 1996 likely caused by the El Niño phenomenon in 1995.
Imports peaked in 1998 at two million tons as a result of the severe El Niño and again reached over one million tons in 2002.
Rice imports during the pre-AFMA period averaged 690,000 tons which grew to an average 840,000 tons from 1999-2004.
Total import expenditure amounted to US$1.27 billion and US$1.13 billion during the pre-AFMA and post-AFMA period, respectively.
Total imports for 2005 reached 1.8 million tons while in 2006, imports are projected at 1.2 million tons.
Comparing the volume indices, it can be seen that there have not been enough spikes in production to abate the seeming periodic surges in imports following the occurrence of an extreme weather disturbance such as the El Niño.
