Cutflowers in Gloom (1)
Rosalie B. Bernardino Researcher Center for Food and Agri Business University of Asia and the Pacific
Cutflowers are blooms cut from the plant and are sold commercially.
They are classified as fresh, dried, dyed or bleached.
Cutflowers are used for corsages, wreaths, or special flower arrangements.
They also serve as additives in perfume processing and other industrial purposes.
Production Almost 1,600 hectares are devoted to cutflower production in the country.
The major varieties grown are gladiola, daisy, rose, orchid, anthurium and chrysanthemum.
Other types are statice, baby's breath, aster, sampaguita, and ilang-ilang.
Most are produced in Benguet.
Packaging sizes vary.
Some are expressed in dozens, others in bundles, tons and pieces.
Combined production of rose, daisy, gladiola, orchid, chrysanthemum and anthurium in 2000 reached 12 million dozens from 10 million dozens in 1999.
Rose and daisy dominate with 30% and 21% share in 2000, respectively.
From 1991-2000, rose production increased by 7% per annum with average produce of 3 million dozens per year from an average planted area of 156 hectares.
In 2000, production went up by almost 60% to 3.6 million dozens from 2.3 million dozens in 1999.
Seventy percent (70%) of the total blooms came from Benguet.
For the past ten years, production of daisy reached an average of 2 million dozens per annum.
Harvest stood at 2.5 million dozens in 2000, with 46% coming from Caraga.
Gladiola production dropped by 5% per year from 1991 to 2000.
In 1996, production fell by 80% to 1.9 million dozens from 9.7 million dozens in 1995, following the drop in area planted by 36% to 407 hectares from 636 hectares.
Benguet was the major producer with 82% of the total harvest in 2000.
Average orchid output for the past ten years was 1.4 million dozens, increasing by almost 13% per annum.
Meanwhile, production in 2000 fell by almost 3% to 1.9 million dozens.
Southern Mindanao produced 41% of the total production while Western Visayas produced 26%.
Annual chrysanthemum production from 1991 to 2000 was 2.8 million dozens, experiencing a 5% drop per year.
Harvests in 2000 rose by 36% to 1.8 million dozens from 1.3 million dozens in 1999.
Major producers in 2000 were Central Visayas at 48% and Cordillera Administrative Region (CAR) at 40%.
During the ten-year period, anthurium production grew by 13% per annum with 268,000 dozens of flowers yearly.
Southern Mindanao and CAR were the leading producers with shares of 27% and 25%, respectively.
Baby's breath and statice production stood at one million bundles in 2000, with the former comprising seventy one (71%).
Average production of baby's breath was 590,000 bundles, up by 14% per year from 1991-2000.
Production slightly declined in 2000 to 757,000 bundles from 765,000 bundles the previous year.
The bulk of output came from Western Visayas and CAR at 73% and 37%, respectively.
About 420,000 bundles of statice were harvested annually from 1991 to 2000.
Production went up by 3% to 307,000 bundles in 2000 from 298,000 bundles in 1999.
Benguet, where almost all of the harvest came from; and Pampanga, which produced only 60 bundles in 2000.
Aster and sampaguita production reached 576 tons in 2000, down by 56% from 1,301 tons in 1999.
Aster production declined by 7% yearly in the past ten years, averaging 800 tons per year.
Production in 2000 plunged by 69% to 284 tons from 914 tons in 1999, with Southern Tagalog as major producer (77% of total harvest).
From 1991 to 2000, sampaguita production increased by 9% per year, averaging 246 tons annually.
Output declined by 25% in 2000 to 292 tons from 387 tons a year ago.
More than 51% of the total flowers came from Southern Tagalog while the Bicol Region produced 36%.
About 112,000 pieces of ilang-ilang were harvested yearly from 1991 to 2000.
Production in 2000 reached 232,000 pieces, with 88% coming from La Union.
According to an industry player, local production is not enough to supply the domestic market.
