A Challenging Task One of the biggest issues that beset the chicken egg industry is the low domestic consumption.
A cross country comparison cited in the layer master plan indicated that the Philippines has a per capita consumption that is similar with Indonesia of 51 eggs/year but far lower than Thailand of 130 eggs/year and China, 300 eggs/year.
Moreover, the Philippines ranked 20th among Asian countries in terms of per capita consumption.
The sector is threatened by the perception that chicken eggs cause high cholesterol levels.
This idea has thwarted the local demand of table eggs.
Also, it is believed that a maximum of only three eggs should be consumed every week.
On the contrary, recent research(5) discloses that an egg a day is beneficial.
The Egg Board regards the situation as a challenge.
It commits to work in order to double or triple egg consumption in the next few years.
With the help of the Department of Agriculture, the Egg Board has started its multi-media campaign by radio and TV commercials to educate consumers on the benefits of eggs and correcting the misconception.
The layer sector may have a long way to go but a unified effort of the egg growers shows a lot of promise.
