• Since 1978, the Chinese government has (PPP) gradually privatized its state-owned industries and companies.
The private sector currently accounts for two-thirds of China’s GDP.
Forecasted economic trends:
• GDP growth reached 9.9% in 2005, fuelled by business investment and a boom in the service sector.
GDP is expected to slow to 9.6% in 2007, from 10.5% in 2006, as the government attempts to reduce China’s reliance on imports and foreign investment, and focus its efforts on increasing consumer spending.
GDP growth of 9.3% is forecast for 2008.
• Chinese exports and imports are expected to reach US$960 billion and US$810 billion respectively in 2006.
This will create a US$150 billion trade surplus, an approximate 50% increase over the 2005 value of US$102 billion.
• General price levels are expected to remain constant at 1.8% in 2006, and decrease to 1.0% in 2007.
Consumer Market Urban vs. Rural Consumers Previously, China’s elite and a small percentage of upper middle-class consumers were wealthy enough to purchase international and Western-style food products.
In fact, nearly 50% of all Chinese households in urban areas are considered middle-class.
This population is projected to reach 40% by 2020, up from 19% in 2003, if current growth trends continue.
Average urban Chinese living supports the ability to allocate considerable amounts of disposable income to imported and domestic consumer goods and services.
Currently 80% of urban homes have refrigerators and washing machines, 50% own air conditioners and DVD players, and a 20% have computers.
Furthermore, automobile sales are rising by 40% per year.
China’s southeastern and coastal regions are typically more urbanized than western and rural parts of the country, due to their proximity to ports and easier accessibility for foreign companies.
To view a breakdown of GDP per capita by province and the economic development differences of urbanized and rural regions in China visit the China Facts page of www.shanghaienglishteachers.com. Nearly 65% of China’s population resided in rural locations in 2005, a figure that is expected to decrease by 16 points to reach its forecasted 2015 value of 56%.
As China’s urbanization increases, its overall prosperity is expected to rise accordingly.
Industry analysts have stated that an urbanization rate of 40-50% lends to more rapid urban growth, and only begins to slow when a nation is 70% urbanized.
China is believed to have reached the 42% urbanization mark in 2005, and is well on track to attain 50% between 2010 and 2015, and 60% by 2030.
By 2010 China’s urban population is expected to be between 650 and 700 million, at least 2.4 times larger than that of the United States and 1.7 times larger than India’s.
Such developments will have a dramatic affect on consumers’ purchasing power and taste for more sophisticated Western products and services in certain high-growth cities.
This change could further boost Chinese consumption of Canadian agri-food products as Western foods, particularly health, natural, organic, and convenience foods, have become popular staples in many urban Chinese diets.
