Only a small portion (13%) of Japan’s total area is suitable for agricultural and Japanese food production continues to decline.
Labor shortages and land-use policies have driven up domestic production costs making imports increasingly competitive.
Japan’s agricultural sector accounts for slightly more than 1% of total GDP and engages about 5% of the population.
It is highly subsidized and is dominated by small farms.
Farms are organized under a large and powerful agricultural cooperative system, which lobbies for high support prices, tariffs on imports and the maintenance of small farms.
Japanese agriculture is centered on the production of rice, livestock, fruits and vegetables.
Rice is Japan’s most significant agricultural commodity, accounting for about one third of gross agricultural income.
Japan has also established offshore production facilities and invested in food processing ventures, particularly in China and Southeast Asia.
These facilities produce products specific to the Japanese market.
