Agri-Food Past, Present & Future Report Australia November 2006
Australia Past Present & Future Report November 2006 Overview Although Australia is located on the opposite side of the world, its similarities to Canada and its market potential continue to bring the countries closer together.
Australia has a rapidly growing population and strong economy.
With about 85% of the country’s population of 20.2 million residing in coastal urban centres, Australia is among the most urbanized populations in the world.
Australia’s relationship with dominant players in the Asia-Pacific region is a key factor in its economic strength and appeal to foreign exporters and investors.
Canadians exporting to Australia will face strict food import standards, but once accepted entry, will find much opportunity.
Canadian exporters of consumer-oriented goods, particularly those exporting pork and food preparations, will continue to achieve the most success in the Australian food industry.
Canada - Australia Relations Canada and Australia have a positive and long-standing relationship that is attributed to many shared qualities: parliamentary traditions, large aboriginal communities, culturally diverse nations, healthy standards of living, as well as continental-sized and geographically dispersed landscapes.
Bilateral visits between Canada and Australia began in 1894 when Canada’s first diplomat, John Short Larke was posted as Trade Commissioner to Sydney.
The most recent visit took place in May 2006 when Australia’s Prime Minister visited Canada.
During the visit, the strong relationship between Canada and Australia was addressed.
Canada and Australia enjoy productive and wide-ranging bilateral relations in areas such as trade, security, defense, immigration, consular affairs, culture, academic and student exchanges and tourism.
Canada Australia Report:
By the end of 2004, Canada was Australia’s 11th largest investor and Australia was Canada’s 14th largest investor.
Canada’s investments in Australia are diverse, focused on food processing, mining and energy, engineering, computer software, and media and communications.
There are over 120 Canadian firms active in Australia, the largest being Placer Dome, Alcan, Nortel and McCain.
• In 2005, Canada’s most important exports to Australia were frozen pork (7.1%), motor engines (5.8%) and iron ore (4.3%).
Agricultural Trade Although Canada and Australia produce similar agricultural commodities, the two countries remain significant trading partners.
In 2005, Australia was Canada's 8th largest agricultural trading partner with bilateral trade exceeding $645.1 million.
Australia was also Canada's 13th largest export market, with exports having exceeded $179.7 million in 2005.
Canadian agri-food, fish and seafood exports to Australia have increased steadily from 2003-2005.
Total exports in 2005 reached $179.7 million, an increase of almost 11% from 2004.
Export opportunities lie in Canadian consumer-oriented goods.
In 2005, these products made up 95% of all agri-food, fish and seafood product exports to Australia.
Successful and Growing Agri-Food Export Products:
• Frozen pork continues to be Canada’s main export to Australia.
In 2005 frozen pork exports totalled $116 million, increasing by 9.8% from the previous year.
Exports of this commodity have steadily increased from 2003.
Blueberries (wild and cultivated, combined) were a high growth export commodity from 2004-2005 and continued to experience success from January-August 2006.
In 2006 (January-August), the market was valued at approximately $1.9 million.
Navy/white pea bean exports have experienced tremendous growth to date in 2006 (January-August totals).
This product is valued at almost $1.2 million and grew roughly 190% from 2005’s full year total.
From 2003-05, navy/white bean exports were relatively insignificant with an average of $270,000.
Consumer-Oriented, Intermediate and Bulk Agri-Food Exports
• Canada’s agri-food exports were comprised mainly of consumer-oriented goods in 2005.
Consumer-oriented goods made up rougly 95% of exports, intermediate goods accounted for 4% while bulk goods contributed very little to exports at 1.2% of the $180 million total.
• In 2005, consumer-oriented exports were valued at $162.5 million and increased 16% from 2004’s total of $140.1 million.
• Canada’s most valuable consumer-oriented exports included: frozen pork (72%), food preparations (9.3%), fresh or chilled pork (2.3%), maple syrup (1.9%), and rye whisky (1.6%).
• Canada’s intermiediate agri-food products for 2005 accounted for approximately 4% of exports and were valued at roughly $6.9 million.
Bovine semen (14.7%), animal feed preparations (12.5%), navy/white pea beans (5.8%), lentils (5.0%), oats (4.4%) and starches (4.1%) were the largest export products.
• Intermediate agri-food exports have dropped since 2003 due to decreased exports of pulses and tallow (fat from beef or mutton).
• Bulk exports contributed the least to total agri-food exports to Australia in 2005, making up only 1.2% of total exports and were valued at almost $2.1 million.
