What's New Canada brand tools showcased at annual meeting of Canada's ministers of agriculture St-John's, NFLD, June 2006 – Canada's efforts to brand Canadian agriculture and agri-food products in international markets were given a boost with the launch of the new branding Canada guide and Web site at the annual conference of federal, provincial and territorial agriculture ministers in St-John's, Newfoundland and Labrador.
Federal Minister of Agriculture and Agri-Food Chuck Strahl and his provincial and territorial counterparts enthused over the Canada brand exhibit, which showcased the new graphics, Web site and recently published branding guide, Quality is in our Nature:
A Guide to Building and Managing the Canada Brand for Food and Agriculture.
The branding strategy and tools—which include a research-based brand promise, consumer and buyer market research in Canada's key export markets and the Canada brand graphics—were developed in close collaboration with industry and provincial and territorial governments.
"This was a great venue to feature and promote the new Canada brand tools," said Sheila Barth, AAFC Branding Strategy Manager.
"To be a success, and give Canadian companies a competitive edge in international markets, the Canada brand strategy needs awareness from all levels of government, as well from the private sector.
This was a great step forward in achieving that."
"The good news is that the research showed that Canada and Canadians already have a positive image on the international stage," Barth said.
"The great news is that industry and government alike now have a series of strategic, research-based tools to take that strong image and leverage it to benefit the entire Canadian food and agriculture sector."
"There was a lot of enthusiasm about the potential of Branding Canada's tools to strengthen the sector's international reputation as a supplier of high-quality and safe foods," she added.
The World Trade Organization negotiations also featured prominently.
International trade is an important component of the Canadian agri-food sector.
Almost half of Canadian domestic food and agricultural production is exported either directly as primary products or indirectly as part of processed products.
Last year Canada exported over $30 billion (Cdn) worth of food and agriculture around the world.
