What's New Pavilion at Foodex Japan wins design award Winnipeg, November 2006 - We knew this year's Canada pavilion at Foodex Japan, developed with the new Canada brand look and graphics, was a hit with stakeholders.
But now it's official!
The Canadian Agri-Marketing Association just awarded it a "Best of CAMA" award in the Merchandising Aids-Exhibits/Displays category at its annual awards banquet held recently in Winnipeg.
It was Canada's 24th consecutive year at Foodex, but the first time the new full Canada brand look and graphics – developed in partnership with industry and provinces – were incorporated into the Canada pavilion.
"It's really rewarding to get this kind of recognition," said Branding Strategy manager Sheila Barth, "especially with so many people involved.
It says a lot for the power of teamwork."
The pavilion was designed by Ottawa design company Oulton and Devine with input from Adculture and Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada's Events Secretariat.
(Adculture is the marketing agency that developed the original Canada brand graphics based on research in Canada's key export markets and with industry and provincial government input.)
"A ‘sense of space' is an actual key Canada brand element," said exhibit designer Peter Oulton, "so immediately the pavilion had to be open concept.
And with such a diverse group of companies in the pavilion, that was a challenge."
"Typically, the Canada pavilion has the exhibitors on the perimeter with an exclusive lounge area in the middle.
But this time, we had to incorporate everything so that all of the exhibitors were visible from all angles and the core services were easily accessible to companies," Oulton said.
"Most visitors prefer to stay on the main aisles, so we had to make it really inviting to get them to come into the pavilion."
It didn't turn out to be a problem—and having Canadian chef Wayne Murphy, in the heart of the pavilion, on hand daily to prepare Asian-style recipes using Canadian ingredients, didn't hurt.
We were able to incorporate larger graphics into the upper areas of the exhibit structure, and in the end everything really worked well," he said.
Close to 40 Canadian companies participated in Foodex, held near Tokyo, Japan, last March.
It's estimated that 2,500 exhibitors and close to 100,000 professional visitors attended the four-day annual event.
