Canada Brand Member Profile Prairie Berries www.prairieberries.com Sandra Purdy is one determined farm business owner, which clearly explains the success of Prairie Berries, a 10-acre Saskatoon berry orchard in Keeler, Saskatchewan.
It comes complete with a federally registered primary processing plant that cleans, grades, freezes and packages the nutty flavoured purplish-blue berries right on the farm.
After a few years of success, a secondary processing plant was added to perfect the company's award-winning gourmet fruit products like fruit toppings, syrups and jams, and yummy pies.
Sandra and her husband Ken first thought about producing Saskatoon berries as part of their farm diversification project back in the early 1990s.
They knew at the time that there was export potential.
The berry was unique, nutritionally valuable and had historically been a stable food source for native North American aboriginals.
But what the Purdys didn't know was how fast an international demand would emerge.
"I say I'm lucky," Sandra explains.
"The exporting really fell into our lap.
We knew that if we wanted to succeed in larger markets, we needed to produce a consistent, quality product," she says.
And then the demand started to grow.
"We started putting our company's name out on government websites…and we just started getting approached by more buyers and large importers."
The Purdys had been working as part of a co-operative grain farm with Ken's father and brother since 1982.
But Sandra had to work off the farm for financial survival.
Then, in the early 1990s, the agriculture buzz became "diversification" and she started thinking.
"My husband loves the farm and likes to work the land and produce food," she says.
"Those things are important to him.
So I knew if we wanted to stay here, we had to be creative."
And creative she was.
She homed in on the Saskatoon berry, a native Prairie berry whose nutrient composition is said to rival, if not exceed, that of the blueberry.
The Saskatoon berry is an adaptable plant that grows under a wide range of environmental conditions.
The berries apparently contain higher levels of fibre, manganese, magnesium, and protein than most other fruit.
It's a unique commodity, and, as an emerging industry, demand currently exceeds supply.
But, like most farming, it's not an endeavour for the faint of heart.
And the payback - it takes four years before a plant bears fruit and seven years before acreage is in full production - slow.
Still, the Saskatoon berry is catching on.
In 1993, 855 acres were estimated to be in production in Saskatchewan, Manitoba and Alberta.
According to Statistics Canada, Canada's international exports of jams and fruit jellies are on the rise, having increased by almost 75 per cent in value between 2003 and 2006 - from $17 million to $29 million (Cdn).
Despite their success the Purdy's aren't even considering hitting the American market at this point.
"Right now, to be a reliable supplier capable of delivering a quality product each and every time, the demand from Germany and the United Kingdom is all we can handle.
I don't dare go down to the States.
That type of smarts fits in perfectly with the philosophy behind the Canada brand program, which Prairie Berries joined as soon as Sandra heard about it in October 2006.
"This program is so in line with what we're doing and what we believe," she says.
"We believe in all the Canada brand attributes of commitment, excellence and quality, customer focus, and trustworthiness, all of which is supported by our reputation for nature and clean, wide-open spaces."
If Prairie Berries couldn't keep up with the demand for its product in the United States, "that would mean we would fail to deliver on those attributes," Sandra points out.
"And that would hurt our company brand, as well as the Canada brand.
That's a chance I won't take unless I'm convinced there's little or no risk involved in that happening."
In order to meet rising international and domestic demands, and to take the Prairie Berries brand to the next level, the Purdys do plan to expand their network of growers and invest in a centralized processing facility that has the technology and capacity to produce new products.
"We need to be innovative and creative.
‘Alberta-made' or ‘Saskatchewan-made' just doesn't cut it in the international market place.
I mean, we're one million consumers here in Saskatchewan and we can't consume all the products we make, so we'll always have to discover new markets."
"Canadian producers have to be creative and change their mind set.
