World Market Overview China The USDA Foreign Agricultural Service (FAS) forecasts China’s pork production in 2007 will reach a record high of 55.8 million metric tonnes (MMT) a 5% increase from the estimated 52 MMT in 20061.
During 2006, China’s wholesale swine prices decreased 27 and 26 percent when compared to prices in 2005 and 2004.
This drop has been linked to high grain wholesale prices.
It is estimated by FAS that the average farmer has been losing $10 USD raising one head of swine, and that some farmers started slaughtering sows as a response to market conditions.
Despite the drop in pork consumption in the last decade, pork remains the dominant traditional animal protein.
The FAS forecasts China’s pork consumption to reach a record high of 55.5 MMT in 2007.
Pork imports into China for 2007 are expected to decrease due mainly to domestic pork production and low pork prices.
Decreased pork imports will be offset by an increase in pork offal imports.
China requires a zero tolerance on the pathogens Salmonella, Listeria and Ecoli (0-157) in 5 samples (total 25 grams) for all kinds of meats.
If these pathogens are detected at entry ports, China will destroy or return the goods.
Because China’s zero tolerance policy on raw meat imports is not based on science, the United States initiated several bilateral talks with China.
The US has negotiated a 45-60 day corrective period for meat plants instead of being de-listed immediately by China.
China began deliveries of fresh pork to Hong Kong in August 2006.
Due to transportation logistics between China and Hong Kong, China pork exports will be very competitive in the Hong Kong market.
European Union As part of the process of applying for membership in the European Union (EU), new member countries had to work on bringing their systems for monitoring the agricultural industry into line with EU requirements.
In comparison with the EU-15 member countries, only Spain and Germany had larger pig populations than Poland at December 2005.
Since 2003 annual pig slaughtering figures for the EU-15 have remained virtually unchanged.
In 2005 compared to the same period in 2004, all producers, except Germany, saw declines or virtually no change in the number of pigs slaughtered.
For 2006, very little pig slaughter data is available.
In the first two months of 2006, Belgium, Denmark and United Kingdom have seen a decline in pig slaughtering while Spain, France and Italy have seen increases.
United States The USDA December 1st Hog report indicates both market and breeding herds have grown just 1% larger than those reported in 2005, showing little response to higher corn prices.
During 2006, cash corn prices rose approximately 36%, increasing cost per finished hog by 10%.
During the period ’04-06, cheap corn and strong pork prices produced 34 consecutive profitable quarters for efficient producers.
Canada Quebec hog prices have been decreasing recently, and have been below Ontario hog prices for several months.
Quebec's Pool price and average Auction price for the second week of October fell $20 and $47, respectively, below Ontario's 100% price of $136.47.
In Ontario weaner/feeder exports have declined by an average of 7% for the period August till December 2006.
During the same period, the export of slaughter barrows and gilts are up by an average of 19% each week.
Provincial slaughter has been up 3% since October partially due to the cheap hog supply available from Quebec.
In the western provinces, weekly feeder pig exports through North Dakota have grown 19% each week from August through the end of 2006.
Meanwhile, during the same timeframe, prairie hog slaughter rates had declined 1%.
China Swine fever fears continued to affect buying interest in some regions.
New-born piglets as well as those that were about one month old were particularly prone to the virus infection.
Nevertheless, farmers were seen taking extra precaution in disease prevention to avoid potential losses.
Those producers who are optimistic about improved hog prices have started to replenish piglets after mid-week December.
With improved hog prices, the recent increase in feed prices had become less of a factor of consideration in farmers' plans to replenish piglets, as gain in income will offset the increase in production cost.
Medium-sized commercial farms were more active in buying piglet supplies than backyard farmers.
