Russian pork imports had increased 38.6 percent over the previous year.
The domestic pork sector growth was slower than previously forecasted for 2005- 2006.
Hog breeding was also behind forecasted numbers for the same period.
However, the pig crop is expected to rebound in 2007.
Due to last year’s lower prices and duties, Russia imported meat in excess of set quotas.
There have been increases in imports from Slovakia and Denmark of pedigree pigs and piglets indicating future changes in pig production.
Russia continues to uphold its ban on all Ukrainian products of animal origin.
United States According to Ron Plain, U.S. pork exports have set a record for the 15th straight year.
During the first 11 months of 2006, the U.S. pork industry exported 2.72 billion pounds (carcass weight equivalent).
U.S. pork exports are expected to be 12% higher than the 2005 figures.
The pork export total for 2006 is expected to be six times the export totals reported in 1993.
The forecast for 2007 is that this trend of growth will continue.
The big growth markets for U.S. pork exports in 2006 were Russia, South Korea and Mexico.
