A Wild Alternative As mentioned, seafood consumers have been "spoiled" by farmed salmon in terms of the consistency of the product: always available, always fresh, always the same size, colour, and flavour.
By providing customers with consistent value, farmed salmon first displaced wild salmon on many seafood shelves around the world, and then expanded the market category substantially.
In the last couple of years, however, there has been a consumer backlash against farmed salmon: not because of customer dissatisfaction with the product itself, but because of highly publicized environmental impacts related to the rearing of the animals and concerns about additives in the feed.
While some consumers remain loyal to farmed salmon, others have turnedoff it completely, and others are increasingly amenable to wild salmon alternatives.
This backlash has provided a real opportunity for wild salmon to regain profile in an expanded market category.
The emerging consumer preference for wild salmon, however, is not a carte blanche for producers to sell poor quality and/or over-priced product to the marketplace.
For wild salmon to gain an enduring position alongside (or as a replacement to) farmed salmon, producers must provide consumers with consistent strong value.
