Japan's regulation allows certifying bodies in foreign countries, which do not have an equivalent system to the Japanese Agricultural Standards (JAS) grading system, to enter into a contract with a Registered Certification Organization to act on their behalf to ensure that imported organic products are in accordance with the specific JAS standards.
One of the requirements that the foreign certifying bodies would need to satisfy is to be accredited by the national government, local government or an international certification organization such as the ISO or the International Federation of Organic Agricultural Movements.
There are three methods for appending the JAS symbol to imported products and labelling them "organic".
Two require that foreign countries have a grading system equivalent to the JAS grading system:
• Foreign Manufacturers or Foreign Production Process Managers certified by the Registered Foreign Certification Organization may conduct the grading in accordance with the procedures stipulated in the specific JAS standards and append the JAS symbol to their products for importation by Japanese importers.
This is limited to the countries which have been set forth by Ministry's Ordinance as having a grading system for agricultural and forest products equivalent to the JAS system.
• Importers, certified by a certification organization whose management system and facilities for handling imported products are in conformity with criteria stipulated by the Minister ("Certified Importer"), may append the JAS symbol for organic foods when accompanied by a certificate or duplicate copy issued by governmental organizations in foreign countries or corresponding institutions designated by the Minister.
This is limited to the countries which have been set forth by Ministry's Ordinance as having a grading system for agricultural and forest products equivalent to the JAS system.
