Organic in Europe Prof Ulrich Hamm introduces the EU wide organic trend At the second Cologne Organic Trade Forum, Prof Ulrich Hamm looked towards Europe.
With €3.9 billion, Germany is by far the largest national market within the European Union, followed by Great Britain with €2.2 billion and France with €1.7 billion.
In all of the three countries, organic foods realized double-digit growth rates in 2005.
However, the per capita consumption in Switzerland (€102), Denmark (€74) and Austria (€55) is higher than in Germany with only €47.
While the Danish and Austrian markets are currently expanding, the Swiss market is stagnating.
The consumption of organic foods in European countries is growing stronger than the area of cultivation.
The situation in Denmark is especially difficult since the cultivation area has been decreasing over the last five years whereas sales increased by 50% at the same time.
England is facing the same situation:
The cultivation area expanded only marginally by 1% whereas consumption rose by 49%.
In the past, goods were mainly exported to the US due to the favourable US$ exchange rate.
The market is about the same size as in Europe, but with very limited domestic production, i.e. high dependence on imports.
There was no discussion about where the products are currently purchased.
But if you have an importer on the one side, there is always an exporter at the other.
The largest producer of organic foods is Italy despite a rather small domestic market.
Spain, whose domestic market is even less developed, is also a leading producer who supplies the markets in the middle European countries.
The favourite distribution channel for organic foods in Europe is the food retail trade.
Only in Germany and The Netherlands, this share is less than 50%.
In Germany, however, the trend goes towards supermarkets.
The reasons to buy organic foods are food safety and regional origin.
Another important motive is the additional benefit "indulgence without a bad conscience" which researchers define as health, animal protection and environment.
The organic consumer of the future is not a homogeneous target group.
His behaviour is impulsive-driven, this means that he has to be won over at the point of sale.
The trade also benefits from the high safety of organic foods, even though the problem of residues is still evident.
However, organic is also a means to distinguish oneself in the food market.
The products are categorized somewhere between basic and additional health benefit and between low and high prices.
The undefined middle segment will be facing hard times.
It can either justify higher prices if it offers additional health benefits or else it can convince with low prices.
With regard to the purchasing sector, there will be a trend towards internationalism which bears the problem of lack of transparency and quality assurance.
"The product quality will be a dominant topic", says Hamm.
Internationalism is a trend which already lasted for some years, but has hardly been noticed until now.
A large number of organic products from hard wheat to rice to olives and coffee have to be imported, since these plants do not grow in this area.
Hamm's outlook until 2010 forecasts a strong market in all of Europe.
According to him, Eastern and Southern Europe will record high growth rates.
The purchasing industry will likely face problems of quantitative and qualitative nature.
Therefore, Prof Hamm recommended that the trade establishes its own supply chain.
