Healthy convenience and consumer attitudes in Europe Pleasure, health and convenience are defined as the three mega-trends in marketing of food today.
Pleasure still comes first for most consumers, which are not ready to sacrifice enjoyment for health and convenience.
Health has become such an important trend that consumers will likely choose health, even where less convenient.
This offers marketing opportunities.
According to a recent report from Reuters there is evidence, that the prevalence of healthy convenience is not accurately captured yet.
Such products still account for a relatively small share of all product launches, with beverages being the category with the highest proportion here.
So there are more opportunities out to enforce healthy convenience, e. g. for:
• Consuming "on-the-go"
• More customized concepts
• Better kids' products Major key trends driving healthy convenience are:
• Personalized nutrition
• Daily dosing
• Physical activity, sports
• Weight management Best prospects are expected for products delivering the healthy benefits consumers want, whilst simplifying their lives.
Attitudes to food fortification Healthiness can be either delivered by addressing the inherent benefits of natural, low-processed foods, or by the addition of nutrients.
But what are the consumer attitudes towards fortification?
For two major groups of nutrients, vitamins and minerals, latest consumer research data are available now.
The HealthFocus© 2006 trend survey is looking into consumer attitudes and actions towards healthy choices.
It helps to understand, what is happening in the market for healthy foods, beverages and supplements.
Trends in consumer awareness, perception and usage of the product categories and ingredients are demonstrated.
Regarding the fortification of foods and beverages with vitamins and/or minerals the acceptance in Europe is very substantial overall.
But fortified products do have their place in the regular consumption patterns indeed.
Some more details for six major European markets, including directional trends covering the situation two years ago are shown here:
• On average, every second Western European (WE) consumer agrees, that it is important to eat foods fortified or enriched with added vitamins/minerals.
Chart 1) Sources of Vitamins and Minerals Strongly agree/agree It is important too eat foods that are fortified or enriched with added vitamins and/or minerals
Chart 2) Food Fortification Attitudes Consumers choose foods/beverages because they are fortified with extra vitamins and/or minerals
• It is most interesting to know whether consumers not only appreciate the addition of vitamins, but see it justified (and are willing) to pay a premium for products that are fortified with extra nutrition.
Indeed 37-49% of the consumers strongly agrees or agrees that such products are worth paying slightly more (chart 3).
Chart 3) Fortification Attitudes and Actions Strongly agree/agree Foods/beverages that are fortified with extra nutrition are worth paying slightly more for.
In conclusion, the European consumer attitudes and actions toward addition of vitamins and minerals are quite favorable.
How is fortification practiced then?
According to data from Mintel (GNPD) on the number of new product launches with added vitamins, the number of launches is still increasing year by year overall in European markets, for almost all food categories.
That does not imply that consumption of products moves in parallel, because also fortified products have got their life cycles, and new launches may show comparable flop rates as ordinary products.
New EU legislation will come into force in the near future by the Fortified Foods Regulation and the Health and Nutrition Claims Regulation.
It will give a harmonized framework for the EU member states and pull down existing trade barriers.
On the other hand many questions will not be answered soon, e. g. on the impact of the coming nutrient profiles.
It is expected fortified foods and beverages will continue to be an important, well accepted and safe option offered in retailers' shelves.
