Geese shortage in Germany Breeding in stables a burden - import prices on the rise The geese production will be even smaller than expected.
In the light of avian influenza and the regulation to breed poultry in stables greatly hampered this year's geese production.
Usually, geese are kept on pastures to run free for several months in Germany.
This was partially impossible or only feasible in some regions as long as strict veterinary regulations were adhered to.
Mainly small companies dreaded the additional effort and discontinued their production.
The smaller supply already reflects in higher prices.
This year's consumer prices in the food retail trade will be between €6.90 and €11.48 per kg, i.e. that the price range has expanded compared to the last year.
With a continuously low domestic production of some 4,000 tons, the self sufficiency rate is only at 14%, therefore most of the domestic demand for geese and geese meat is met by imports (29,000 tons in 2005).
They mainly come from Poland and Hungary in form of frozen whole geese.
The imported products are usually sold at a special price in the food retail trade, whereas German geese are mainly sold fresh, often directly from the producer, on weekly markets and in food specialty shops.
Besides, they can often be found on menu cards of the HRI industry.
The import volume is expected to decline in 2006.
Due to the limited supply, import prices are well above last year's level, and no one knows how this will reflect on consumer prices.
As usual, there will be huge price differences between fresh and frozen products from Germany and abroad.
In 2006, domestic and foreign suppliers are expected to meet the demand for duck and duck meat.
