Last week, Doris Leuthard, Minister for Economic Affairs, announced to renew the Federal Law on Technical Trade Barriers (Bundesgesetz über die technischen Handelshemmnisse THG).
This would mean that Swiss distributors and European importers could more easily trade food products, household appliances, textiles and cosmetics in Switzerland.
Until now, special regulations have been preventing or hampering import and trade activities.
They required that many products had to be re-labelled, re-tagged or re-licensed to be distributed in Switzerland.
Apart from high agricultural subsidies, Swiss regulations were the main reason why many products are much more expensive in Switzerland than in the EU.
In order to fight this 'high-price island', the Federal Council wants to introduce the 'Cassis-de-Dijon' principle.
This principle - developed by the European Court of Justice in 1979 -aligns most Swiss product regulations with those of the European Union.
Thus, Minister Leuthard intends to reduce the current number of exemptions in Switzerland (120) to only 40.
Meanwhile, an official hearing has been opened, which means that interest groups, political parties and administration groups can comment and make a demand on this proposal.
Besides, the Minister for Economic Affairs wants to fight discrimination of Swiss producers.
The draft law of the Federal Council demands that Swiss producers will be able to produce their goods according to EU regulations and distribute them in Switzerland.
But it could take some time until the drafts turn into concrete laws.
What is most important is that the new Federal Law on Technical Trade Barriers needs to be resistant to any referendum, says a Swiss trade specialist [who wants to remain anonymous].
Swiss farmers will fight any liberalisation of the market.
"If farmers threaten with a referendum, the procedure can drag on for several years", explains the specialist.
It would be 'sensational' if the new law came into force on 1st January 2008; 2009 would be more likely.
However, the Interest Group of Swiss Distributors (IG DHS), which counts Coop, Denner or Migros among their members, is convinced that this development cannot be held back.
The direct import allows Denner to sell the tooth paste for CHF 1.00 less than their competitors, says Eva-Maria Bauder, Press Spokeswoman of Denner and IG DHS.
According to estimates of Rudolf Strahm (who monitors product prices), foreign producers realize CHF 25 to 30 billion through their high price policy.
Trade experts anticipate that foreign distributors like Aldi Suisse will profit the most.
The new regulations will make it easier for the German discounter to position long-standing suppliers in Switzerland.
The Spokesman with Aldi Suisse, however, did not want to comment on this.
