"The agreement facilitates the agricultural trade through reduction or abolition of non-tariff trade barriers, i.e. certain technical regulations concerning veterinary medicine, plant protection, organic agriculture and quality norms for fruits and vegetables etc. will be mutually accepted.
The indications of origin for wines and spirits are equally protected; other sectors, especially the cheese sector, can be included later on", summarizes the official notification of the Swiss government.
Now another proposal has been brought forward: free trade with the EU, which was presented in the Federal Council in mid February.
All political parties were surprised and their reactions were strong.
Whereas some spoke of a 'death blow against Swiss agriculture', others saw this as 'the only possibility to survive'.
It is beyond any doubt that the agricultural sector, which realizes an annual income of CHF 3 million, will face drastic cuts.
Taking the EU free trade zone as an example, the agricultural information agency talks about a 50%-reduction of the income.
Under the motto 'Agricultural Policy 2011" other models are discussed to increase the competitiveness of the Swiss agriculture through reduction of market support, abolition of export subsidies and increase of direct payments.
These models also talk about severe losses for the farmers: their turnover is to decline by CHF 500 million.
Another item on the agenda is negotiations with the WTO which plans a worldwide liberalisation of the agricultural trade.
No matter what the results of the negotiations might be - a thorough structural change of the agricultural sector is merely a matter of time.
The processing industry has long been waiting for this.
High prices for raw materials and tariff barriers on top of high incidental costs did nothing to improve Swiss competition.
On the other hand, Swiss products are already well represented on the international market.
"Switzerland still stands for high prices", says Lorence Weiss of baking material manufacturer 'Jowa', "but if we specialise consequently and in a professional way, we can well be competitive on a European level".
Export figures show how well Swiss companies are represented abroad; exports increased overall in the last year and account for more than 50 % of the turnover.
This is true for brand producers of cheese and confectionery as well as for private labels, which are typical of processed foods.
It is time to orientate towards a larger internationalism.
The Swiss price system finally started to sway due to the market entry of large foreign retailers who offered their products at lower prices and purchased more goods from abroad than Migros or Coop.
But it seems that "Swiss companies are still at the beginning of a large fight for quality and price-conscientious customers", says Prof Dr Thomas Bogner from Lörrach, who studied the Swiss trade environment intensively.
However, the first effects on prices are already visible.
No. 3 in Europe Switzerland remains one of the ten most competitive countries of the world.
On the list of the Lausanne Institute for Management Development (IMD), Switzerland maintained last year's position, ranking 8, reported Swissinfo.
The United States stayed on the top of the list.
At the same time, Switzerland is among the top three European countries, following Island (ranking 4th on the global list) and Denmark (ranking 5th).
The study, which has been conducted since 1989, examines 61 countries and regions and their position in the international market based on a catalogue of 312 criteria.
One of them is the "work environment" of companies in each country.
The most important factors are hard facts like economic situation, economic and political efficiency and infrastructure, but manager surveys are also taken into account.
With their finance system and their excellent credit rating, Switzerland ranked first in two different categories.
The strength of the Swiss economy is also reflected in Swiss investments abroad: here, Switzerland ranks 4th.
Switzerland to open up to the EU market At last week's annual press conference of Weko, the Swiss Commission of Competition, Weko President Prof Walter Stoffel called for an uncompromising market opening towards the European Union.
Prof Stoffel proposed to apply the Cassis-de-Dijon principle in the trade with EU member states.
This means that all products which can freely circulate throughout the European market could also be freely traded in Switzerland.
The Swiss government is preparing a market opening to improve the competitiveness of the Swiss market.
However, some press releases report that a number of Federal Offices applied for more than 100 exceptions to a general free circulation of goods in order to hold on to divergent national regulations which control, among others, the access to dangerous chemicals or the labelling of GMOs.
Slight drop of organic consumption in Switzerland The number of organic farms declined slightly in 2005 for the first time in the 25-year history of Bio Suisse.
The structural change in agriculture does not even stop for organic.
The overall organic market did hold its ground at a high level, however - despite the raw headwind from the cut-price shelves.
Turnover steadied at 1.183 billion CHF (752 million EUR), slightly less than 0.5 % below the previous year, but the dynamic differed in the individual submarkets.
Sales of organic fruit, organic vegetables and organic eggs grew strongly, but organic meat and organic milk slowed.
The Swiss remain world champions with per head spending of 160 CHF (101 EUR) on organic products.
6,114 farms in Switzerland - some 11 % of all farms - currently work according to the Bio Suisse guidelines. www.biosuisse.ch Source:
