Clear upswing in imports and exports During the first nine months of 2006 there was a clear upswing in German confectionery imports and exports.
According to the BDSI, imports rose 10.8% in volume up to 654,175 tonnes worth €1.734 billion (bn), an increase of 6.6%.
Confectionery exports were up 7.2% on the previous year in volume, to total 896,759 tons worth €2.439 bn, up by 6.9%.
Exports of chocolate confectionery- the most important segment-grew at above market average rates of 15.3% in volume (229,840 tons) and of 15.2% in value (€881.2 m).
The German exporters of snacks benefited most from the boom generated by the fascinating 2006 World Cup, hosted by Germany.
Exports of sugar confectionery increased between January and September by 4.0% in volume (120,531 tons) and by 5.3% in value (€311 m).
Exports of fine pastries, in contrast, dipped by 6.5% down to 177,477 tonnes, which are worth €488.7 m (-5.8%).
Double digit growth in imports of snacks The increase in demand for snacks also impacted on imports, which rose by 15.9% in volume to 59,826 tonnes worth €149.8 m - a rise of only 2.9%.
In terms of percentages, growth in imports of chocolate confectionery (128,958 tons, €474.1 m), fine pastries (130,784 tons, €316.3 m) and sugar confectionery (88,635 tons, €255.7 m) was all single digit.
Imports of cocoa and chocolate semi-finished articles rose by 30.4% in volume up to 181,746 tons worth €390.6 m (+14.0%).
The Netherlands strengthens leading position 574,420 tons of confectionery from the EU (+8.4%) worth €1.496 bn (+5.4%) was imported by Germany.
Imports from the Netherlands-the biggest exporter to Germany- rose 11.2% in value up to €487.9 m.
