Sugar-frees to take the offensive Less fat and sugar - the sweets and confectionery industry is facing the obesity discussion and the looming advertising ban.
With new initiatives and innovations, the industry tries to take the wind out of critics' sails.
The International Trade Fair for Sweets and Confectionery (ISM) in Cologne made it clear that the health and wellness wave has caught the sweets and confectionery industry.
The focus was on sugar-free and fat reduced products, which meet customers' demand for balanced nutrition and indulgence without bad conscience.
This does not come as a surprise, since sweets have never been so harshly criticized than today.
Growing problem of obesity It is a fact that more than 200 million adults and 14 million kids in Europe are overweight or obese.
Hence, it is understandable that in light of these figures, EU politicians want to send a message.
Whether a ban on advertising for confectionery will cause children to eat less chocolate and sweets is, however, highly debatable.
"A ban on advertising will not solve the problem", says Philippe Metzger, CEO of Masterfoods.
However, the share of obese children is as high as in any other Canadian province, where there is no such ban.
This indicates that there is no connection between confectionery advertising and obesity.
The best example is the country with the highest per-capita consumption of chocolate in Europe:
Switzerland. Every Swiss consumes an average of 11 kg of chocolate per year.
However, the share of obese people in relation to the total Swiss population is lower than in any other country in Europe.
The Greeks eat an average of only 3 kg of chocolate per year, but there is no other country in Europe with a higher percentage of obese people.
Steps towards a better image Despite the all-clear, the industry is actively promoting healthy nutrition.
Already three years ago, leading manufacturers (e.g. Masterfoods, Nestlé, Ferrero, Kraft Foods, Intersnack and Katjes) have joined the platform 'Peb' (Initiative Platform Nutrition and Exercise).
The first result of this platform is 'Peb & Pebber', an animated puppet cartoon to motivate kids to exercise more and eat healthier.
Some manufacturers even have gone a step further.
Masterfoods, for example, no longer offers snack bars with more than 300 cal.
They also changed the product recipes and reduced the content of trans fatty acids by 90% to less than 0.5 grams per serving.
Moreover, product developers are fiercely working on a way to improve the share of health-beneficent flavonoids in Masterfoods' products.
Their commitment to indicate not only the calorie content but also its percentage share of the recommended daily intake is groundbreaking.
Besides, Masterfoods does not show advertisements addressed to under twelve-year-olds in Germany.
Other sweets manufacturers are working on similar measures.
