Fish consumption reached a record high in 2006.
The fastest growing sector in the food production is aquaculture.
For three consecutive years, German per-capita consumption of fish and seafood increased by another kilogram to 15.7 kg in 2006.
Fish is already as popular as poultry.
Though the figures of the Hamburg association are still preliminary, the trend is also confirmed by other sources.
The market research institute GfK has calculated that German households bought more fish between January and November 2006 than in the same period last year - despite significant price increases.
According to the GfK household panel, sales rose by only 0.5%, whereas the turnover of fish in the food retail trade was up by almost 6%.
There is a simple reason for the discrepancy between figures provided by the wholesale trade and the food retail trade: the latter accounts only for one part of the fish sales.
Households continue to buy about half of the fresh fish in specialty stores or on weekly markets.
Already in 2005, GfK calculated an increase in volume of 1.4%, compared to an increase in turnover of 3.5%.
Consumers are well-prepared to pay more for this trend product.
Although prices for fresh fish rose by almost 5% to an average of €10.00 per kg, this did not slow down the turnover: +1.5%.
The winners of the growing popularity of fish are, among others, supermarkets' fresh food counters.
They account for 11% of the overall fish sales.
The development of frozen fish and fish marinades is very similar, reports GfK:
Frozen fish has become the most important fish product with a market share of 32%.
Part of the success is due to the market entry of the discounters.
Supermarket customers are more price-sensitive when it comes to smoked or canned fish.
A rather high-priced distributor like 'Erftland-Forelle' recorded double-digit growth rates for Irish salmon - both in terms of volume and value - despite supply shortages.
The canned food segment, with products like herring in tomato sauce, still recorded a minor growth in turnover, although sales declined by 3%.
Only so-called 'other fishery products' like matjes herring, fish pâtés etc. recorded marginal decreases both in terms of value and volume.
This was the motto of 'Real's' latest fish weeks (Real is a subsidiary of Metro Group).
Fish from all over the world is no longer shipped by boat but by air freight/plane.
Thus, Frankfurt airport is now ranking first on the list of the most important ports of entry, followed by fishing harbours like Bremerhaven and Cuxhaven.
In 2005, the Center for fish information (FIZ) determined the importance of fish on the food market.
The study revealed that new species like the Asian catfish, New Zealand hike 'hoki', Victoria Perch and pike perch each account for 1 to 2%.
Their market shares in terms of value, however, are much higher due to the over-proportional prices.
Their annual growth rates are between 30 and 75%.
Fish retailers react with flexibility to the increasing shortage of traditional fish species.
Herring, cod and plaice are rare; classic species like sole and turbot are sold at delicatessen prices.
The gap between supply and demand is already growing, although fishing regulations imposed by the European Union are less stringent than required by scientists.
Aquaculture fish is gaining in importance.
Although frequently proclaimed, there are hardly any differences in quality between farmed fish and wild fish.
The gourmet magazine "Der Feinschmecker" took the chance of inviting fish retailers and chefs de cuisine to test five fish species, ranging from organically farmed to wild caught.
On a seminar in Hamburg, sector specialist Dr. Manfred Klinkhardt explained that the term 'aquaculture' comprises a broad range of methods and techniques:
But also in Germany, best-sellers like trout and carp are farmed in ponds.
Floating net cages on seashores mainly produce migrating fish like salmon and salt water species.
While yields in the fishing industry fluctuate by 90 million tons per year, the worldwide aquaculture production increased from 20 million tons in 1990 to more than 60 million tons.
Aquaculture is most common in Asia.
More than 54 million tons or 90% of the worldwide production comes from Asia, thereof 41 million tons from China.
However, the most important product is not fish or prawns but kelp, a water plant of which Japan alone produces 4.5 million tons per year.
The second most important product is Pacific rock oyster, whose production quadrupled over the last ten years, now accounting for 4.4 million tons.
The aquaculture production separates into 28 million tons of fish, 13 million tons of molluscs like mussels and snails and 3.7 million tons of crustaceans.
Shrimp farming in the North Sea The by far largest part of this production only has an indirect impact on the German or European market - despite the worldwide competition for raw materials.
The Asian carp production is twenty times larger than the European, but hardly anything of it reaches the European market.
When thinking of farmed fish, we mostly refer to carp, salmon and trout.
The worldwide annual production of these migrating fish amounts to 3 million tons, thereof 1.2 million tons Atlantic salmon.
Farming of saltwater fish species like bass, seabream, tuna and turbot accounts for only 1.4 million tons - not enough to relieve the world's overfished oceans.
But this sector is growing rapidly, and smaller amounts can have a huge effect on turnover.
Shrimp, for example, represents only 6% of the aquaculture production, but secures one fifth of its turnover.
The Dutch Fish Bureau recently announced that farming of tropical prawns and Australian lungfish (barramundi) has been resumed on the Dutch coast.
Water warmed by energy plants enables farming of these species even in our regions.
However, an annual production of 30 tons will go unnoticed by our Southeast Asian competitors.
Major German retailer Lidl supports sustainable fishing by offering MSC-labelled products Lidl, one of the largest German retailers, has introduced a range of one smoked and seven frozen fish products carrying the Marine Stewardship Council's (MSC) eco-label.
The company has initially introduced the products to its 3,000 stores in Germany and Austria and intends to grow this range and extend its use of the eco-label into other European countries.
Lidl is also committed to encouraging its supply fisheries to seek certification to the MSC's environmental standard for well-managed and sustainable fisheries.
While over 450 products in retail chains in 25 countries carry the MSC mark, Lidl is the first discounter to do so.
The new MSC line has been produced under the company's private labels "Ocean Trader" and "Ocean Sea".
The range consists of seven products made of Alaska pollock and one made of Alaska salmon.
Fisheries targeting both species have been identified by independent experts as meeting the MSC's environmental standard for well-managed and sustainable fisheries.
To date, 22 fisheries are certified to the MSC standard and a total of over 50 fisheries are engaged in the MSC programme.
Together, they record annual catches of more than 3.5 million tonnes of seafood.
They represent 42% of the world's wild salmon catch, 32% of the prime whitefish catch, and 18% of the lobster catches for human consumption.
