Organic is gaining momentum Biofach presents trends - premiere for Vivaness The business of organic products is flourishing all over the world.
Experts forecast a turnover of clearly more than US$ 30 billion.
Biofach, held from Feb 15-18, 2007 in Nuremberg, underlines this trend with rising exhibitor and visitor numbers.
Organics, the market of the future, is growing.
But the boom does not only affect organic foods, but also natural cosmetics.
This is one of the reasons why the world's leading trade fair has allocated a separate hall to these products and celebrates the premiere of 'Vivaness'.
A total of 2,100 exhibitors will be presenting a comprehensive product range to some 37,000 visitors.
Organic is moving on, also in Germany.
The German Farmers Association (Deutscher Bauernverband DBV) forecasts an amount of €5 billion for 2007.
However, the German food retail trade sources an increasing number of products abroad, as Germany is running short of raw materials.
The huge demand is facing declining numbers of farmers willing to change to organic cultivation, now that Federal Länder and the EU have cut subsidies.
On the trade side, organics have developed into a trend product with which each distribution channel tries to distinguish itself.
Discounters have also entered the market - the latest to launch its own organic brand was soft discounter 'Penny'.
The current consumer panel for organic products, conducted by Lebensmittel Zeitung through interviews with readers of the online paper 'LZ-Net', reveals that 500 of the distributors interviewed expect an average price increase of 20%.
Two thirds of the interviewees are open to foreign products, but 47% of the industry and 40% of the trade are convinced that the product quality is below that of German products.
A niche product is dressing up Those who think much of themselves are buying organic.
Those who still think of organics as a niche product for eco freaks have definitely missed a trend.
A broad line of organically produced products has long found its way into the food retail trade.
The turnover with organic products has been rising steadily since 2000, as statistics of the Center for Market and Price Reporting have shown.
In 2005, this turnover amounted to almost €4 billion, which means that each household spent almost €45 for organic food.
But there are many different reasons for buying organic products.
A recent study of market researcher AC Nielsen revealed that the classic reasons which prevailed at the beginning of the organic movement like animal welfare (29%) and environmental protection (12%) have faded into the background.
Nowadays, 37% of consumers like to do something good for themselves and choose organic products because of their higher value of health.
Thus, consumers do not mind that organically produced products are still more expensive than conventional goods.
When renouncing chemical-synthetic treatment or fertilizers, the crop is about one third below that of conventional farmers.
The risk of crop shortfall is also higher.
It can be expected that the price margin of organic products will increase further.
"Customers can soon choose from a broad variety of organically produced products, reaching from low-priced to premium products", says Christoph Soika of Organic Consulting CSB/CSC.
The product variety will also be growing.
The share of organic products within a product group still varies significantly according to the figures of the Federal Agency for Agriculture and Food (BLE).
Bread and bakery products rank second with 12%, followed by meat and sausage products (10.5%) and herbs and spices (10.4%).
Frozen food is among the last of the ranking - only 1.7% of this product group is marked with the organic seal.
However, we cannot leave the growing market to foreign suppliers", says Harald Gabriel, CEO of Bioland.
In order to solve the problem in the long run, more German farmers would have to change to organic farming.
Until then there might be the danger that imported organic products would lead to strong competition among suppliers, fears Christoph Soika.
The pressure to deliver could provoke manipulations and might dilute the quality of organic products.
What can the trade do to offer organic products and - in the long run - ensure quality for their clients?
Loyal, reliable suppliers can ensure a steady supply."
