News and Information Outstanding Success for Canada's Winemakers  Canadian Wines Triumph in Italy
Canadian wines achieved an outstanding success at the 40th VINITALY, the international wine exhibition closing up today in Verona, northern Italy.
Canada also garnered a record of: 1 Gold medal, 1 Silver medal, 1 Bronze medal and 20 Grand Mentions.
The Special Prize Vinitaly 2006, the second highest prize at stake (for winemakers) has gone to Jackson Triggs Vintners Okanagan Estate (Oliver).
The latter received two of the Grand Gold Medals for its Syrah Okanagan Valley VQA "Sun Rock Vineyard" 2003 (red wines, vintages 2003-2005) and Cabernet Sauvignon Okanagan Valley VQA Grand Reserve 2002 (red wines, vintages 2000-2002).
The other two Grand Gold Medals went to the Pillitteri Estate Winery, Niagara on the Lake, for its Vidal Icewine Niagara Peninsula VQA 2004 and Vidal Sparkling Icewine Niagara Peninusula VQA 2004, respectively.
Magnotta Winery Corporation, Vaughan Ontario, took home a gold medal thanks to its Riesling Icewine Niagara Peninsula VQA 2003.
Canadian Ambassador Robert Fowler and Consul General Margaret Huber heartily congratulated the Canadian companies attending Vinitaly, including Grand Gold Medal winner Pillitteri Estate Winery.
They also called Jackson-Triggs Vintners to congratulate the firm on its Grand Gold Medal awards.
VINITALY, held in the biggest wine-producing country in the world, is considered by winemakers the most prestigious event of the year.
3,482 wines from 30 different countries participated in this 14th edition of the international wine competition.
