From March 31 to April 22, Canadian products were featured in 60 gourmet shops, 60 restaurants and over 50 supermarkets and cafeterias.
Developed in partnership with El Corte Inglés (ECI), this integrated promotion introduced our products to the restaurant industry and to retail sales outlets throughout the Iberian Peninsula (Spain and Portugal).
The exercise, made possible by the cooperation and efficiency of Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada (AAFC), made a remarkable contribution to the development of Canada's brand image through a major media campaign.
The association with the ECI, Spain's largest distribution chain with annual sales of 14 billion euros, was supported by a Canadian partnership deftlly spearheaded by AAFC.
Canadian provinces and associations (mainly Ontario, Quebec and B.C.) worked with AAFC to organize specific buyer programs in order to identify products that meet the buyer's strict selection criteria.
The project was in line with AAFC's strategic priorities, i.e.: promoting value-added products (bison meat, cranberries, ice wines, etc.), introducing new products to hotels, restaurants and institutions (sauces, preserves, seafood, etc.) and offering new Canadian products to a young, upscale clientele that enjoys discovering new culinary options.
Most Canadian products that meet these criteria are made by young Canadian SMEs seeking new export markets.
• Increase the number of active exporters to Spain, the 3rd-largest European market for Canadian agri-food products, fish and seafood
• Increase exports of high value-added food products
• Develop Canada's brand image in Spain and Portugal
• Develop a special relationship with El Corte Inglés, Spain's largest retailer.
THE PROJECT: 1.
Planned an integrated promotion at Gourmet Clubs, megastores supermarkets, restaurants and cafeterias simultaneously, so as to reach different types of consumers; 2.
Introduced 100 value-added products representing purchases of close to C$1 million; 3.
Delivered a major promotional campaign in Spain: radio, newspapers and specialty magazines based on value-added products and Canada's cutting-edge approach (see attached article); 4.
Printed 40,000 ECI catalogues on Canadian products available during the event, sent to ECI's best clients and available at Gourmet Clubs (attached); 5.
Published 40,000 copies of a 23-page article on Canada in ECI's Gourmet magazine, sent to ECI's best clients and also available at Gourmet Clubs; 6.
Translated AAFC's recipe book, "Canada, l'excellence à votre table" ["Canada, excellence at your table"] and published 4,000 copies distributed to ECI's best clients, journalists and Embassy contacts to promote the use of Canadian products at home; 7.
Printed 500 tabs with a photo of the recipe book sent to the Embassy's best contacts to publicize the book; 8.
Printed 2,000 high-end menu cards sent to ECI restaurants with Canada's brand image; 9.
Trained 60 chefs from ECI's top restaurants in July 2005 for the menu created by a Canadian chef in partnership with Clearwater and the Canadian embassy (activity report attached); 10.
Organized an ECI buyers' mission in September 2005; 11.
Published a 4-page article in the weekly glossy supplement "Fuera de Serie" in "Expansión", Spain's largest economic paper; article published for the occasion, focusing on gourmet foods in Canada, including the cover page (article attached - following message); 12.
Two official inaugurations were organized, one in Vigo and the other in Madrid.
The Madrid inauguration launched the promotion with a ribbon cutting where the press and product tastings preceded a restaurant meal for 60 guests featuring the Canadian menu.
The Vigo inauguration was an opportunity for lobbying national and regional fishery industry authorities, who were also invited to taste the Canadian menu (100 guests participated in the Vigo event).
THE RESULTS: 1.
ECI purchased almost $1 million worth of some 100 products from all sources (see attached list of products found in stores); 2.
The budget for organizing the event was 91,400 euros, plus VAT; 3.
Permanent listing of certain wine, cider and preserve products (repeat orders by ECI); 4.
Resolution of problems accessing the Spanish market for lesser known products such as: wild rice, special preserves, maple products or alcoholic beverages (improved market access); 5.
We are negotiating with ECI to follow up on this activity, particularly by organizing a "seafood products" promotion for the 2006?2007 holiday season.
CHALLENGES AND LESSONS LEARNED:
The timing of this activity coincided with Canada's seal hunt.
Campaigns against the hunt and the resulting negative publicity led to the cancellation of certain press and communication events.
Overall, the crisis was effectively managed by minimizing public activities.
Organizing an activity simultaneously in two countries was a challenge.
ECI's Portuguese section does not appear to have followed through on all of its obligations, which resulted in the cancellation of most activities in Portugal.
I take this opportunity to thank Dianne Guindon, AAFC's Senior Officer, Europe, who was instrumental to this major promotion.
