Snow crabs are caught in traps, from sandy bottoms in depths of 1 to 470 metres.
The Canadian fishing season runs from April to November.
Commercially caught crab measure from 9.5 to 15 cm in width and weigh from 350 g to 1.3 kg.
When cooked, the shell of the snow crab turns bright orange.
The meat has a rich, sweet flavour and firm texture.
Orangey-pink on the surface and white inside, the meat of the snow crab is composed of fine, tender filaments that are exquisitely mild and tasty.
