Salmon The Atlantic salmon is born in fresh water and remains there until it undergoes a physiological transformation allowing it to tolerate salt water.
After one to three years at sea, the salmon returns to its river of origin to spawn.
It therefore has two distinct habitats: freshwater rivers and the ocean.
On British Columbia’s Fraser River, the largest salmon river in the world, sockeye are managed under strict conservation practices.
