Wild Rice Wild rice, derived from the wild aquatic grass called Zizania aquatica, grows naturally in the pristine lakes of Manitoba and Saskatchewan.
In the early days, this most delicious staple of the First Nations of Canada was harvested entirely by hand.
The grain was dried over wood fires, "danced" upon in pots to remove the hulls, and winnowed clean using birchbark pans and the wind.
Today, wild rice is harvested mechanically, with a harvest area being picked over as many as eight times to complete the harvest.
